  "text": "When Grafana executes a log query to a Loki datasource, the call chain flows as follows:\n\n1. **Grafana's HTTP Client (grafana/grafana)**: The LokiAPI struct in pkg/tsdb/loki/api.go acts as the HTTP client for Loki queries. The Service in loki.go creates a LokiAPI instance and calls its DataQuery method (line 267 in loki.go). The LokiAPI.DataQuery method constructs an HTTP request via makeDataRequest (line 168 in api.go) which builds a GET request to /loki/api/v1/query for instant queries (line 88 in api.go). The request is sent using api.client.Do(req) at line 176 in api.go.\n\n2. **Loki's HTTP Request Parser (sg-evals/grafana-loki)**: On the Loki side, the incoming HTTP request to /loki/api/v1/query is decoded by the Codec.DecodeRequest method in pkg/querier/queryrange/codec.go (line 328). For instant queries, this method identifies the operation type as InstantQueryOp (line 345) and calls parseInstantQuery(r) (line 346). The parseInstantQuery function (line 2255 in codec.go) then calls loghttp.ParseInstantQuery(r) from pkg/loghttp/query.go (line 2256). This ParseInstantQuery function (defined at line 402 in query.go) is the primary function that parses incoming HTTP instant query requests, extracting the query expression, timestamp, limit, direction, and other parameters from the HTTP request form."
}

